To study the degree (extent) of personalization of PersFL and to compare it with the other personalization approaches, we average experiments of CIFAR-10 and MNIST datasets over 555 experimental runs for each data-split.
Table¬†2 and Table¬†3 show the per-user accuracy of Fed-Avg, PersFL, FedPer, pFedMe, and Per-FedAvg on different datasplits of CIFAR-10 and MNIST.
Below, we present the performance of PersFL with the FedAvg model and the best performing algorithm on the average accuracy across users.

Our analysis of CIFAR-10 in Table¬†2 shows that PersFL performs better than other personalization techniques across all data-splits.
In comparison to the FedAvg model, PersFL leads to a percentage increase of ùüæùü∏%percent82\mathtt{82\%}, 22.3%percent22.3\mathtt{22.3\%}, and 76.6%percent76.6\mathtt{76.6\%} on DS-1, DS-2, and DS-3.
For the compared approaches, for all data splits, PersFL improves the on average accuracy by 4.7%percent4.7\mathtt{4.7\%}, 0.6%percent0.6\mathtt{0.6\%} and 3.9%percent3.9\mathtt{3.9\%} across users compared to FedPer, pFedMe, and FedPer respectively.
The absolute improvement of PersFL over other techniques on DS-1, DS-2 and DS-3 is 3.7%percent3.7\mathtt{3.7\%}, 0.4%percent0.4\mathtt{0.4\%} and 3.1%percent3.1\mathtt{3.1\%}, compared to FedPer, pFedMe, and FedPer.

We compare PersFL with the best performing method in terms of average accuracy.
In CIFAR-10 experiments (Table¬†2), PersFL yields a SD of 4.94.9\mathtt{4.9} among the average accuracy of users on DS-1, which is the least deviation compared to the other approaches.
This yields a reduction of 1.14‚Äãùö°1.14ùö°\mathtt{1.14x} in SD compared to FedPer.
For DS-2, pFedMe yields an SD of 1.41.4\mathtt{1.4}, slightly better than 1.71.7\mathtt{1.7} SD of PersFL.
For DS-3, PersFL achieves a reduction of 1.10‚Äãùö°1.10ùö°\mathtt{1.10x} in SD compared to FedPer.

To study the degree (extent) of personalization of PersFL and to compare it with the other personalization approaches, we average experiments of CIFAR-10 and MNIST datasets over 555 experimental runs for each data-split.
Table¬†2 and Table¬†3 show the per-user accuracy of Fed-Avg, PersFL, FedPer, pFedMe, and Per-FedAvg on different datasplits of CIFAR-10 and MNIST.
Below, we present the performance of PersFL with the FedAvg model and the best performing algorithm on the average accuracy across users.

The results of our experiments on MNIST in Table¬†3 show that, in comparison to the FedAvg model, PersFL improves the accuracy on average by 7.1%percent7.1\mathtt{7.1\%}, 2.9%percent2.9\mathtt{2.9\%}, and 3.1%percent3.1\mathtt{3.1\%} on DS-1, DS-2, and DS-3.
PersFL performs similar to the other approaches.
In DS-1, the best-performing approach Per-FedAvg gives 98.9%percent98.9\mathtt{98.9\%} accuracy, which performs slightly better than 98.6%percent98.6\mathtt{98.6\%} accuracy of PersFL.
In DS-2, PersFL gives a 0.4%percent0.4\mathtt{0.4\%} increase in accuracy across users compared to Per-FedAvg.
In DS-3, both PersFL and FedPer gives 99.4%percent99.4\mathtt{99.4\%} accuracy.

For MNIST (Table¬†3), we observe similar results compared to the experiments on CIFAR-10.
For DS-1, although Per-FedAvg with an average 98.9%percent98.9\mathtt{98.9\%} accuracy is better than PersFL‚Äôs 98.6%percent98.6\mathtt{98.6\%} accuracy, PersFL leads to a 1.5‚Äãùö°1.5ùö°\mathtt{1.5x} reduction in SD compared to it.
For DS-2, we find that the SD of Per-FedAvg at 1.01.0\mathtt{1.0}, is lower than the SD of PersFL at 1.31.3\mathtt{1.3}. On DS-3, the reduction factor for PersFL in SD stands at 1.67‚Äãùö°1.67ùö°\mathtt{1.67x} compared to FedPer.
Overall, PersFL often leads to a reduction in the SD of the average accuracy across users, thus leading to a more uniform (fair) distribution than the compared methods.

Table¬†4 and Table¬†4 show the results of using FedAvg and optimal teacher for CIFAR-10 and MNIST datasets.
We make the following observations in terms of the average per-user accuracy.
On DS-1, initializing with the optimal teacher model leads to a percentage increase of 1.2%percent1.2\mathtt{1.2\%} and an absolute increase of ùü∑%percent1\mathtt{1\%}.

In the case of DS-3, there is a 0.8%percent0.8\mathtt{0.8\%} percentage and 0.7%percent0.7\mathtt{0.7\%} absolute increase attributed to initialization with optimal teachers.

We conduct the same experiments on the MNIST dataset and present the results in Table¬†4.

We argue that this variation can be attributed to the lack of inter-class variations in the MNIST dataset.

We conduct experiments to understand distillation‚Äôs effectiveness by investigating the values of the optimal distillation parameters chosen by each user‚Äôs student model.
Table¬†5 shows the average values of distillation parameters, imitation (ŒªùúÜ\mathtt{\lambda}) and temperature (ùöÉùöÉ\mathtt{T}), averaged out over the five experimental runs on CIFAR-10 and MNIST datasets.
For CIFAR-10, we observe that the ŒªùúÜ\mathtt{\lambda} parameter values are non-zero across users and data-splits.
This observation means that distillation is effective, and the teacher model‚Äôs knowledge is useful in learning the student model.
In contrast, in the case of MNIST, we observe that ŒªùúÜ\mathtt{\lambda} parameter values are mostly very close to ùü∂0\mathtt{0} in the case of DS-1 and DS-3.
We believe that this is because of the nature of the MNIST dataset i.e.,¬†due to the lack of inter-class variations.
We show a detailed analysis of the variation of the classification accuracy on the test-set across users depending on the values of the distillation parameters ŒªùúÜ\mathtt{\lambda} and ùöÉùöÉ\mathtt{T} in the Appendix¬†A.

Table¬†6 shows the results of both variants of PersFL across all data-splits on both CIFAR-10 and MNIST datasets.
We make the following three observations.
First, in MNIST, both variants of PersFL on DS-1 and DS-3 have a very similar performance in terms of average accuracy across all users.
In DS-2 PersFL has an absolute performance improvement of 0.7%percent0.7\mathtt{0.7\%} compared to PersFL-GD.
Second, the performance difference is relatively more in CIFAR-10 experiments.
PersFL has an absolute improvement of 1.4%percent1.4\mathtt{1.4\%} on DS-2 of CIFAR-10 and an improvement of 0.6%percent0.6\mathtt{0.6\%} on DS-3.
In all cases, PersFL performs better than or at least equal to PersFL-GD.
Lastly, in terms of the standard deviations between the per-user accuracy, both PersFL and PersFL-GD yield very similar performance.
